Elastic rebound theory in an animation: http://earthquake.usgs.gov/learn/animations/animation.php?flash_title= El 	  astic+Rebound&flash_file=elasticrebound&flash_width=300&flash_height=350 . Elastic rebound theory. Stresses build on both sides of a fault, causing the rocks to deform plastically (Time 2). When the stresses become too great, the rocks break and end up in a different location (Time 3). This releases the built up energy and creates an earthquake. 
Focus and  Epicenter 	  In an earthquake, the initial point where the rocks rupture in the crust is called the focus. The epicenter is the point on the land surface that is directly above the focus ( Figure 6.19). 
