Several cirques from glaciers flowing in 	  different directions from a mountain peak, leave behind a sharp sided horn, like the Matterhorn in Switzerland. (d) When glaciers move down opposite sides of a mountain, a sharp edged ridge, called an arête, forms between them. 
Snowmelt and melting glaciers combine 	  to create a fast moving stream at Glacier National Park. 
