Local  Surface  Currents 	  The surface currents described above are all large and unchanging. Local surface currents are also found along shorelines ( Figure 8.40). Two are longshore currents and rip currents. Rip currents are potentially dangerous currents that carry large amounts of water offshore quickly. Look at the ripcurrent animation to determine what to do if you are caught in a rip current: URL motion/currents2.htm . Each summer in the United States at least a few people die when they are caught in rip Longshore currents move water and sediment parallel to the shore in the direction of the prevailing local winds. currents. This animation shows the surface currents in the Caribbean, the Gulf of Mexico, and the Atlantic Ocean off of the southeastern United States: URL . 
Summary 	  • Major surface ocean currents are the result of global wind patterns, Earth’s rotation, and the shape of the ocean basins. • Major surface currents circle the oceans in five gyres. • Local surface currents, like longshore and rip currents, move near shorelines. 
