Marine  Invertebrates 	  The variety and number of invertebrates, animals without a backbone, is truly remarkable ( Figure 10.21). Marine invertebrates include sea slugs, sea anemones, starfish, octopuses, clams, sponges, sea worms, crabs, and lobsters. Most of these animals are found close to the shore, but they can be found throughout the ocean. Jellies are otherworldly creatures that glow in the dark, without brains or bones, some more than 100 feet long. Along with many other ocean areas, they live just off California’s coast. Learn more about jellies by watching URL . Click image to the left or use the URL below. 
